{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12732"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12732"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.68,0.09,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81309"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5187"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66651"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"3752"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44289"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81309"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue. She reports feeling cold and has numbness in both feet. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never smoked and drinks five standard drinks of alcohol per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her tongue is smooth and erythematous. She has reduced proprioception at the ankles bilaterally and absent ankle reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 69 g/L (115-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMean cell volume 129 fL (80-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 3.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 110 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood film shows macro-ovalocytes and hypersegmented neutrophils\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypothyroidism","Liver disease","Pernicious anaemia","Alcohol-related macrocytosis","Myelodysplastic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of macrocytic anaemia, neurological symptoms, and pancytopenia suggestive of vitamin B12 deficiency. The blood film showing macro-ovalocytes and hypersegmented neutrophils is characteristic of megaloblastic anaemia, which occurs due to impaired DNA synthesis affecting rapidly dividing cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPernicious anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis, caused by autoimmune destruction of gastric parietal cells leading to decreased intrinsic factor production and subsequent vitamin B12 malabsorption. The combination of neurological symptoms (peripheral neuropathy with reduced proprioception and reflexes) and glossitis is highly characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol-related macrocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically produces a less severe elevation in MCV (rarely \u003E110 fL). While chronic heavy alcohol use can cause vitamin B12 deficiency through poor dietary intake and malabsorption, this patient\u0027s modest alcohol intake of five standard drinks per week makes this very unlikely. The neurological findings and blood film changes are also not typical of alcohol-related macrocytosis alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a mild macrocytosis but rarely to this degree, and would typically present with other features such as bradycardia, weight gain, and cold intolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause macrocytosis through membrane alterations but would typically present with other features such as jaundice, spider naevi, or biochemical liver dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyelodysplastic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause macrocytosis and pancytopenia but typically affects older patients and would not cause neurological symptoms. The blood film would show dysplastic features rather than megaloblastic changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pernicious anaemia is caused by autoimmune destruction of gastric parietal cells leading to decreased intrinsic factor production and vitamin B12 malabsorption","Vitamin B12 deficiency classically presents with macrocytic anaemia, neurological symptoms, and pancytopenia","Blood film findings of macro-ovalocytes and hypersegmented neutrophils are characteristic of megaloblastic anaemia"],"references":["Green R, Dwyre DM. Evaluation of Macrocytic Anemias. Semin Hematol. 2015 Oct 1;52(4):279\u201386."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66651"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12732"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66651"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T20:22:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T20:23:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5187"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81309"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1887"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Vitamin b12 deficiency","synonyms":["Pernicious anaemia","b12/folate deficiency"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2023-04-25T10:31:06+09:30","updatedAt":"20